WEBVTT

1
00:01:01.094 --> 00:01:03.698
<i>Day 42. session 72.</i>

2
00:01:04.799 --> 00:01:06.266
<i>Start recording.</i>

3
00:01:06.801 --> 00:01:08.036
<i>Vitals?</i>

4
00:01:08.168 --> 00:01:10.103
<i>Blood pressure 110 over 70.</i>

5
00:01:10.237 --> 00:01:11.238
<i>Pulse 68.</i>

6
00:01:11.371 --> 00:01:12.674
<i>Vitals normal.</i>

7
00:01:12.807 --> 00:01:15.743
<i>Dr. Kask. what did you see?</i>

8
00:01:16.544 --> 00:01:18.012
<i>What did they show you?</i>

9
00:01:20.048 --> 00:01:21.381
<i>Dr. Kask?</i>

10
00:01:22.584 --> 00:01:24.251
<i>Dr. Kask?</i>

11
00:01:26.386 --> 00:01:28.056
<i>How are you still alive?</i>

12
00:01:49.711 --> 00:01:51.311
<i>How am I still alive?</i>

13
00:01:57.484 --> 00:01:58.886
<i>We're a flawed species.</i>

14
00:02:01.756 --> 00:02:04.626
<i>Okay. are you ready</i>
<i>to meet your little sister?</i>

15
00:02:12.232 --> 00:02:14.902
<i>We're impossibly fragile.</i>

16
00:02:15.870 --> 00:02:17.270
<i>Hi. Klara. Hi.</i>

17
00:02:17.404 --> 00:02:18.539
<i>Yeah.</i>

18
00:02:18.673 --> 00:02:19.974
Do you think
we should keep her?

19
00:02:21.475 --> 00:02:22.844
Yeah.

20
00:02:29.817 --> 00:02:31.052
<i>We're self destructive.</i>

21
00:02:40.895 --> 00:02:42.462
<i>Superstitious.</i>

22
00:02:48.903 --> 00:02:50.237
<i>Driven by fear.</i>

23
00:02:57.444 --> 00:02:58.813
<i>By love.</i>

24
00:03:03.483 --> 00:03:07.254
<i>Barely able to survive</i>
<i>on our tiny blue rock.</i>

25
00:03:09.791 --> 00:03:12.894
<i>let alone in the endless</i>
<i>black ocean of our universe.</i>

26
00:03:13.027 --> 00:03:14.996
<i>Top bunk!</i>

27
00:03:18.866 --> 00:03:20.768
What's past the last planet?

28
00:03:22.003 --> 00:03:23.270
Infinity.

29
00:03:27.008 --> 00:03:28.341
<i>Everything.</i>

30
00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:30.343
<i>Anything.</i>

31
00:03:31.244 --> 00:03:32.847
Whoa.

32
00:03:33.948 --> 00:03:35.516
Nothing ever lasts.

33
00:03:36.551 --> 00:03:38.019
<i>How am I still alive?</i>

34
00:03:42.657 --> 00:03:43.991
<i>We need to let it go.</i>

35
00:03:45.325 --> 00:03:47.061
It needs to breathe.

36
00:03:54.669 --> 00:03:57.939
<i>One day. we will die.</i>

37
00:04:02.143 --> 00:04:03.544
Hey. you okay?

38
00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:06.914
<i>Mom?</i>

39
00:04:07.048 --> 00:04:08.549
Mom! Mom!

40
00:04:10.151 --> 00:04:11.786
<i>We become dust.</i>

41
00:04:11.919 --> 00:04:13.487
Oh my God. what happened?

42
00:04:13.621 --> 00:04:15.255
Klara! Klara!

43
00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:20.194
<i>And our dust</i>

44
00:04:20.327 --> 00:04:23.564
<i>joins all the other</i>
<i>dust of the universe.</i>

45
00:04:29.103 --> 00:04:30.638
<i>And everything we love...</i>

46
00:04:34.709 --> 00:04:35.977
<i>Goes away.</i>

47
00:04:40.982 --> 00:04:42.583
<i>How am I still alive?</i>

48
00:04:45.186 --> 00:04:47.588
<i>How are any of us?</i>

49
00:04:54.195 --> 00:04:57.799
<i>What if biological life</i>
<i>is just a stage?</i>

50
00:04:58.266 --> 00:04:59.834
What if we can evolve?

51
00:04:59.967 --> 00:05:04.839
So our future as a species
is post-biological?

52
00:05:05.573 --> 00:05:08.276
Our present is post-biological.

53
00:05:08.743 --> 00:05:12.780
It took us six thousand years to
go from leeches to pacemakers.

54
00:05:12.914 --> 00:05:13.881
But from pacemakers

55
00:05:14.015 --> 00:05:16.483
to genetically modifying
human embryos.

56
00:05:16.617 --> 00:05:18.119
it took just 60.

57
00:05:18.252 --> 00:05:21.055
Mm-hmm.
So this isn't the future.

58
00:05:21.222 --> 00:05:22.723
The future is right now.

59
00:05:22.857 --> 00:05:24.491
Let me ask you this though.

60
00:05:24.625 --> 00:05:27.028
if our destiny
is post-biological.

61
00:05:27.161 --> 00:05:29.997
is there other life
in the universe as well?

62
00:05:31.032 --> 00:05:33.400
Oh. that's a stone cold
certainty.

63
00:05:34.168 --> 00:05:35.102
Okay. wait. wait.

64
00:05:35.236 --> 00:05:36.403
Here's what I want to know.

65
00:05:37.104 --> 00:05:41.108
Is there something
you know that we don't?

66
00:05:41.242 --> 00:05:44.111
Look. people call me
a tech visionary.

67
00:05:44.245 --> 00:05:45.847
That's just a bunch
of horseshit.

68
00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:50.651
I'm just a fellow that sees
what's right in front of him.

69
00:05:50.785 --> 00:05:53.321
And it ain't no secret
that I made my first billion

70
00:05:53.453 --> 00:05:55.223
from solar energy.

71
00:05:55.556 --> 00:05:57.925
but I did not invent the sun.

72
00:05:58.659 --> 00:06:00.094
I'm no visionary.

73
00:06:01.529 --> 00:06:07.168
Visionaries see things
that no one else does.

74
00:06:09.270 --> 00:06:10.738
and that's rare.

75
00:06:11.706 --> 00:06:14.141
Okay.
so who does Sam Houston

76
00:06:14.275 --> 00:06:15.843
consider a visionary?

77
00:06:18.411 --> 00:06:19.547
Well. you know what?

78
00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:22.250
We have one right here
in this very room.

79
00:06:27.487 --> 00:06:28.756
Annika Kask.

80
00:06:31.391 --> 00:06:32.392
Annika Kask.

81
00:06:32.526 --> 00:06:34.362
would you please
raise your hand?

82
00:06:37.365 --> 00:06:38.866
There she is.

83
00:06:39.499 --> 00:06:44.105
The first person
to photograph dark matter.

84
00:06:50.344 --> 00:06:52.179
- That's it.
- There you go.

85
00:06:52.313 --> 00:06:53.714
Fantastic. Thank you.

86
00:06:53.848 --> 00:06:55.049
- Well. you bet.
- Thank you so much.

87
00:06:55.182 --> 00:06:56.117
Thanks for having me.

88
00:06:56.250 --> 00:06:57.118
Appreciate it.

89
00:06:57.251 --> 00:06:58.252
That was really great.

90
00:06:58.386 --> 00:06:59.287
Nobody got hurt.

91
00:06:59.419 --> 00:07:00.888
Oh. uh. excuse me.

92
00:07:03.958 --> 00:07:05.226
Annika?

93
00:07:05.359 --> 00:07:06.928
- Hi.
- Hey.

94
00:07:07.295 --> 00:07:09.096
Big fan. Big fan.

95
00:07:09.563 --> 00:07:11.899
Thank you. I'm flattered.

96
00:07:12.033 --> 00:07:15.703
Well. uh. I have a confession
to make.

97
00:07:16.704 --> 00:07:19.407
I didn't come here
just to do a TED Talk.

98
00:07:21.309 --> 00:07:23.277
I want to offer you a job.

99
00:07:27.949 --> 00:07:29.784
You know. most people.

100
00:07:30.151 --> 00:07:33.187
they look at the universe
and it's empty.

101
00:07:33.321 --> 00:07:36.991
And you. with one image.
proved 'em all wrong.

102
00:07:37.959 --> 00:07:39.193
How'd you do it?

103
00:07:43.664 --> 00:07:45.533
Every time we'd try
and image it.

104
00:07:45.666 --> 00:07:47.034
we'd get chaos.

105
00:07:47.802 --> 00:07:49.036
Couldn't find
the right data set.

106
00:07:49.170 --> 00:07:50.204
What was the right set?

107
00:07:50.338 --> 00:07:51.205
All of them.

108
00:07:51.906 --> 00:07:53.207
At once.

109
00:07:53.341 --> 00:07:55.209
Overlapping. Like 3D glasses.

110
00:07:55.343 --> 00:07:56.877
Except instead
of just red and blue.

111
00:07:57.011 --> 00:08:00.214
we overlap 233 data sets

112
00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:01.983
to find order in the chaos.

113
00:08:02.116 --> 00:08:04.618
And then you get that.

114
00:08:05.586 --> 00:08:07.321
Well. that's the how. but...

115
00:08:09.357 --> 00:08:10.691
why?

116
00:08:13.594 --> 00:08:15.663
No one's ever asked me
that before.

117
00:08:19.166 --> 00:08:23.004
I guess I just want to know
what's out there.

118
00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:25.139
You want to know
what's out there?

119
00:08:25.272 --> 00:08:26.674
Why not down here?

120
00:08:29.810 --> 00:08:31.178
It's a one-year contract.

121
00:08:31.979 --> 00:08:36.183
Small lab on a remote island
in the Caribbean.

122
00:08:36.317 --> 00:08:37.351
What lab?

123
00:08:37.485 --> 00:08:39.020
That's confidential.

124
00:08:39.987 --> 00:08:42.690
You need scientists
to work on a secret project

125
00:08:42.823 --> 00:08:44.492
on a remote island
in the Caribbean?

126
00:08:44.625 --> 00:08:45.860
Let me tell you something.

127
00:08:47.361 --> 00:08:48.863
There's more up there.

128
00:08:49.864 --> 00:08:51.098
and down here.

129
00:08:51.232 --> 00:08:52.099
Everywhere.

130
00:08:52.233 --> 00:08:53.401
Aliens.

131
00:08:59.974 --> 00:09:03.110
Look. Mr. Houston.
I appreciate the offer.

132
00:09:03.244 --> 00:09:05.780
but I'm not the kind of
scientist who hunts for aliens.

133
00:09:05.913 --> 00:09:07.516
We're not hunting.

134
00:09:08.716 --> 00:09:09.917
We're gathering.

135
00:09:11.018 --> 00:09:14.555
And we need your discovery
to make sense of it.

136
00:09:15.556 --> 00:09:16.857
Look.

137
00:09:17.425 --> 00:09:19.960
you can forget
about your little green men.

138
00:09:20.394 --> 00:09:22.596
fishing for radio waves.

139
00:09:22.730 --> 00:09:24.965
and hunting for a needle
in a haystack.

140
00:09:25.099 --> 00:09:27.435
because I'm here to tell you
that the whole haystack

141
00:09:27.568 --> 00:09:29.570
is made out of needles.

142
00:09:29.937 --> 00:09:31.772
We're not alone in the dark.

143
00:09:32.606 --> 00:09:36.944
In fact. the darkness
has been our company all along.

144
00:09:39.447 --> 00:09:41.215
You want to find out?

145
00:09:57.465 --> 00:09:59.834
<i>I am an electronics engineer.</i>

146
00:10:00.935 --> 00:10:01.902
Charlie Kaminsky.

147
00:10:03.704 --> 00:10:05.139
Sorry. it's just...

148
00:10:05.873 --> 00:10:08.642
Charlie Kaminsky saying
he's an electronics engineer

149
00:10:08.776 --> 00:10:12.279
is like Stephen Hawking
saying he teaches math.

150
00:10:12.413 --> 00:10:15.983
Yeah. I'm the CTO
of Gateway Labs.

151
00:10:16.585 --> 00:10:18.853
Sam hired me to check
some new toys he's building.

152
00:10:18.986 --> 00:10:20.522
Now. where do you-
where do you work. Annika?

153
00:10:20.654 --> 00:10:21.755
R.I.T.

154
00:10:22.623 --> 00:10:24.125
You're Annika Kask?

155
00:10:24.258 --> 00:10:25.326
Yeah. wow.

156
00:10:25.459 --> 00:10:27.161
How did. uh.
how did Sam land you?

157
00:10:27.294 --> 00:10:29.630
He promised me
we weren't hunting for aliens.

158
00:10:30.631 --> 00:10:31.932
You?

159
00:10:32.333 --> 00:10:33.701
He promised me we were.

160
00:10:36.804 --> 00:10:38.005
Oh. wow.

161
00:11:06.033 --> 00:11:07.401
Welcome to the island.

162
00:11:07.536 --> 00:11:08.802
Thank you.

163
00:11:08.936 --> 00:11:10.539
Uh. how many people are
working out here right now?

164
00:11:10.671 --> 00:11:11.672
Nine or ten.

165
00:11:11.805 --> 00:11:13.707
Dr. Glassner
likes to keep it small.

166
00:11:14.543 --> 00:11:15.644
Perry Glassner?

167
00:11:17.711 --> 00:11:19.346
Wow. Shit. Okay.

168
00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:21.916
Yeah. super friends unite.
I like it.

169
00:11:22.049 --> 00:11:23.350
We'll see to your luggage.

170
00:11:23.484 --> 00:11:25.419
Dr. Glassner is waiting for you
in the main facility.

171
00:11:25.554 --> 00:11:26.754
Great.

172
00:11:27.354 --> 00:11:29.990
Oh. um. I'll-I'll catch up.

173
00:11:30.124 --> 00:11:31.158
Here. just be careful with--

174
00:11:31.292 --> 00:11:32.693
Yeah. it's delicate.

175
00:11:32.826 --> 00:11:33.827
- Thank you so much.
- No problem.

176
00:11:33.961 --> 00:11:34.862
Thank you. Thank you.

177
00:11:34.995 --> 00:11:37.164
Perfect. Oh. there we go.

178
00:11:37.298 --> 00:11:38.432
You can take that one for me.

179
00:11:38.567 --> 00:11:39.733
Thanks.

180
00:12:52.206 --> 00:12:53.240
What's this?

181
00:12:53.642 --> 00:12:55.409
B12 methylphenidate.

182
00:12:55.543 --> 00:12:57.111
Immuno-booster.

183
00:13:11.091 --> 00:13:13.360
You shatter a bone and it heals.

184
00:13:13.494 --> 00:13:15.796
but you bruise trust
and it's fatal.

185
00:13:18.332 --> 00:13:19.567
What's your purpose?

186
00:13:20.234 --> 00:13:21.703
I'm Dr. Annika Kask.

187
00:13:22.403 --> 00:13:24.104
Well. that's a chair
I can sit in

188
00:13:24.238 --> 00:13:26.106
and that's a door
I can walk out of.

189
00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:28.208
so what is your purpose?

190
00:13:29.143 --> 00:13:30.444
Sam Houston sent me.

191
00:13:30.578 --> 00:13:31.845
Why would he do that?

192
00:13:34.114 --> 00:13:35.282
I'm a computer scientist.

193
00:13:35.416 --> 00:13:37.017
Oh. right.

194
00:13:37.985 --> 00:13:39.286
That's a shame.

195
00:13:40.187 --> 00:13:41.388
That's a shame.

196
00:13:41.523 --> 00:13:43.324
I thought you might have the
salt to admit the truth.

197
00:13:43.457 --> 00:13:46.661
that you've been sent here
by Sam to spy on me.

198
00:13:47.696 --> 00:13:50.064
To be the bruise that kills me.

199
00:13:51.932 --> 00:13:52.900
Should I go?

200
00:13:53.033 --> 00:13:54.569
No. no. no. no. no. no.

201
00:13:55.269 --> 00:13:58.005
After all.
I might need an algorithm.

202
00:13:59.306 --> 00:14:01.543
Oh. Dr. Glassner. hi.
I'm Charlie.

203
00:14:01.676 --> 00:14:04.546
And I gotta tell you. man.
from one scientist to another--

204
00:14:04.679 --> 00:14:07.081
Here we go.
They're fucking multiplying.

205
00:14:09.950 --> 00:14:12.319
I blew it. I...

206
00:14:13.655 --> 00:14:14.689
As per your NDAs.

207
00:14:14.823 --> 00:14:16.256
communications are monitored.

208
00:14:16.390 --> 00:14:17.726
You will be watched.

209
00:14:17.858 --> 00:14:19.326
It feels like overkill.

210
00:14:19.460 --> 00:14:21.362
Yes. it's completely
and utterly unnecessary.

211
00:14:21.495 --> 00:14:24.164
I should be doing this work
on my own in my basement.

212
00:14:24.298 --> 00:14:27.502
but Sam would never allow that
because this isn't really a lab.

213
00:14:27.635 --> 00:14:30.204
It's a shrine
to a man's overwhelming hubris.

214
00:14:30.337 --> 00:14:32.873
See. most billionaires
buy yachts or football teams.

215
00:14:33.006 --> 00:14:35.744
but he wants to buy ideas
or legacies to show the world

216
00:14:35.876 --> 00:14:38.345
he's somehow changed
the course of human history.

217
00:14:39.146 --> 00:14:40.615
So that's what you do here?

218
00:14:43.384 --> 00:14:44.885
That's what we're about to do.

219
00:14:45.653 --> 00:14:48.288
<i>Welcome to the Tuning Lab.</i>

220
00:14:49.890 --> 00:14:52.727
So you. you're up to speed?

221
00:14:52.861 --> 00:14:55.764
That dark matter
algorithm you discovered.

222
00:14:56.096 --> 00:14:57.732
you'll need to apply it here.

223
00:14:57.866 --> 00:14:59.701
Is this what I think it is?
Does it work?

224
00:14:59.834 --> 00:15:01.969
No. Yes.
And get the fuck away from it.

225
00:15:02.436 --> 00:15:03.738
- Right. Where to begin?
- Sorry.

226
00:15:03.872 --> 00:15:06.608
Let's begin at
the beginning. uh. in darkness.

227
00:15:06.741 --> 00:15:10.444
So let there be light
and heat and bacteria.

228
00:15:10.578 --> 00:15:11.746
single-celled organisms.

229
00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:13.480
Skip a few billion years.

230
00:15:13.615 --> 00:15:15.149
Reptiles. monkeys. then us.

231
00:15:15.282 --> 00:15:16.618
Apex predators.

232
00:15:16.751 --> 00:15:17.786
Petty. ain't we?

233
00:15:17.918 --> 00:15:19.086
Cruel.

234
00:15:19.219 --> 00:15:20.755
Prone to self-destruction.

235
00:15:20.889 --> 00:15:21.989
Hell bent on rage.

236
00:15:22.122 --> 00:15:23.924
fucking our habitat
out of existence.

237
00:15:24.057 --> 00:15:25.794
So now we turn our eyes
away from Earth

238
00:15:25.926 --> 00:15:27.729
in search of other worlds
to defile.

239
00:15:27.862 --> 00:15:29.229
But there's a hitch.

240
00:15:29.363 --> 00:15:32.132
Because Mr. Drake's equation
tells us that we're not alone.

241
00:15:32.266 --> 00:15:33.802
The universe is too vast.

242
00:15:33.934 --> 00:15:35.102
rich with resources.

243
00:15:35.235 --> 00:15:37.471
likely swimming
with intelligent life.

244
00:15:37.605 --> 00:15:38.673
Competition.

245
00:15:38.807 --> 00:15:39.940
And most of that's
going to be millions.

246
00:15:40.073 --> 00:15:42.777
if not billions
of years ahead of us.

247
00:15:42.911 --> 00:15:45.245
So we come into this race
far. far behind.

248
00:15:45.379 --> 00:15:46.581
Nevertheless.
we do start looking

249
00:15:46.714 --> 00:15:49.617
with whatever crude tools
are available.

250
00:15:49.751 --> 00:15:50.919
As you know. SETI.

251
00:15:51.051 --> 00:15:52.787
the Search for Extraterrestrial
Intelligence.

252
00:15:52.921 --> 00:15:54.656
has been scanning. uh. what?

253
00:15:54.789 --> 00:15:56.658
Oh yeah. radio waves.

254
00:15:56.791 --> 00:15:58.125
That still only covers. what.

255
00:15:58.258 --> 00:15:59.960
one ten-millionth
of the night sky

256
00:16:00.093 --> 00:16:02.797
using hilariously
outdated technology.

257
00:16:02.931 --> 00:16:05.533
It's like taking a little bowl
of water out of the ocean

258
00:16:05.667 --> 00:16:08.135
and peering in and concluding
that whales don't exist.

259
00:16:08.268 --> 00:16:09.436
No. not radio.

260
00:16:09.571 --> 00:16:11.104
That's not how
you'd communicate

261
00:16:11.238 --> 00:16:13.641
<i>if you're an interplanetary</i>
<i>intelligence. is it?</i>

262
00:16:13.775 --> 00:16:16.977
You want to talk across space
and time instantaneously.

263
00:16:17.110 --> 00:16:18.111
So let's do this.

264
00:16:18.245 --> 00:16:20.715
Take two photons.
pair them. keep one here.

265
00:16:20.849 --> 00:16:22.650
send the other
light years away.

266
00:16:22.784 --> 00:16:24.686
Force one photon
into a declared state.

267
00:16:24.819 --> 00:16:26.987
and the other responds
in the very same moment

268
00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:28.957
across space and time.

269
00:16:29.089 --> 00:16:30.558
String a few billion
of those together.

270
00:16:30.692 --> 00:16:32.827
and you've got
an FTL communicator.

271
00:16:32.961 --> 00:16:35.630
No. but-but the quantum
communication can't work.

272
00:16:35.763 --> 00:16:36.764
It breaks the laws of physics.

273
00:16:36.898 --> 00:16:39.333
No. no. it bends the laws
that we know.

274
00:16:39.466 --> 00:16:40.735
and that's not what this is.

275
00:16:40.869 --> 00:16:42.904
No. if you force
a quantum state change.

276
00:16:43.036 --> 00:16:44.271
that breaks entanglement--

277
00:16:44.404 --> 00:16:46.306
This machine
does not force a state change!

278
00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:48.576
It doesn't entangle
or disentangle.

279
00:16:48.710 --> 00:16:50.244
It just hears
when someone has.

280
00:16:50.377 --> 00:16:52.580
This simply listens.

281
00:16:52.714 --> 00:16:54.014
It's impossible.

282
00:16:54.147 --> 00:16:56.718
And yet here we have a machine
that does exactly that.

283
00:16:56.851 --> 00:16:59.721
that I built six years ago
in my basement.

284
00:16:59.854 --> 00:17:01.756
on my own on amphetamines.

285
00:17:01.890 --> 00:17:03.892
So. take a look for yourself.

286
00:17:05.292 --> 00:17:06.828
What do you want us to do?

287
00:17:07.629 --> 00:17:08.830
Well. here's a hint.

288
00:17:09.029 --> 00:17:10.732
You've already done it.

289
00:17:14.836 --> 00:17:17.371
It says he's scanning
the radius of a couple of feet.

290
00:17:17.505 --> 00:17:18.573
<i>Right here.</i>

291
00:17:18.706 --> 00:17:21.241
So if he's listening for aliens.
then it's...

292
00:17:21.375 --> 00:17:22.376
He's doing it right here.

293
00:17:22.510 --> 00:17:23.678
in this-in this room.

294
00:17:24.044 --> 00:17:25.880
But-but what is it?
I mean. like these are just--

295
00:17:26.014 --> 00:17:27.549
It's-- It's a ton
of data points.

296
00:17:27.682 --> 00:17:29.684
It's-it's-it's
like background noise

297
00:17:29.817 --> 00:17:30.885
of anywhere in the universe.

298
00:17:31.019 --> 00:17:32.554
There's no rhyme
or reason behind it. It's...

299
00:17:32.687 --> 00:17:33.588
It's chaos.

300
00:17:33.721 --> 00:17:34.722
Yeah.

301
00:17:39.928 --> 00:17:42.030
Then we find order
in the chaos.

302
00:17:54.274 --> 00:17:55.910
Sort by data sets.

303
00:17:59.379 --> 00:18:00.380
Okay.

304
00:18:01.916 --> 00:18:03.718
It's the same algorithm.

305
00:18:05.787 --> 00:18:07.220
It's my algorithm.

306
00:18:09.857 --> 00:18:13.093
Sort by exponents.

307
00:18:13.928 --> 00:18:15.495
It's organizing.

308
00:18:18.198 --> 00:18:20.100
Sort by primes.

309
00:18:21.301 --> 00:18:23.571
What? W-what is this?

310
00:18:24.471 --> 00:18:25.673
I can't believe this.

311
00:18:27.609 --> 00:18:29.677
Overlay all.

312
00:18:34.114 --> 00:18:35.817
It's-it's a signal.

313
00:18:38.251 --> 00:18:40.187
They're talking.

314
00:18:48.462 --> 00:18:49.496
Holy shit!

315
00:18:52.332 --> 00:18:53.768
Dr. Glassner?

316
00:18:57.505 --> 00:18:58.873
Dr. Glassner!

317
00:18:59.007 --> 00:19:00.875
He's only
scanning one little area.

318
00:19:01.009 --> 00:19:02.142
But if it's quantum
communication.

319
00:19:02.275 --> 00:19:03.210
then it-it's all around us.

320
00:19:03.343 --> 00:19:04.846
Or there's another explanation.

321
00:19:04.979 --> 00:19:06.213
Or another phenomenon
that we're not seeing. or--

322
00:19:06.346 --> 00:19:08.850
Or. Annika.
it's fuck-to-the-yes aliens.

323
00:19:08.983 --> 00:19:10.317
- Dr. Glassner.
- I mean.

324
00:19:10.450 --> 00:19:11.853
we've been looking
millions of light years away

325
00:19:11.986 --> 00:19:12.987
for-for smoke signals.

326
00:19:13.121 --> 00:19:14.187
but they were around us
the entire time.

327
00:19:14.321 --> 00:19:15.890
It's...

328
00:19:16.024 --> 00:19:16.891
Is this real?

329
00:19:17.025 --> 00:19:17.892
You tell me.

330
00:19:18.026 --> 00:19:19.661
You're here to check my math.

331
00:19:19.794 --> 00:19:21.696
I mean.
this means...

332
00:19:21.829 --> 00:19:22.864
It means we're not alone.

333
00:19:22.997 --> 00:19:24.532
we're not the centre
of the universe.

334
00:19:24.666 --> 00:19:25.800
we're not special.

335
00:19:25.933 --> 00:19:27.167
It means they don't know
anything about us.

336
00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:28.536
<i>or they don't give a fuck.</i>

337
00:19:28.670 --> 00:19:29.570
What are they saying?

338
00:19:29.704 --> 00:19:31.039
How could I possibly know?

339
00:19:31.171 --> 00:19:33.041
We'd have to ask them with that.

340
00:19:34.274 --> 00:19:35.308
What is that?

341
00:19:35.977 --> 00:19:36.911
Littlemouth.

342
00:19:37.045 --> 00:19:38.378
You're talking to them?

343
00:19:38.513 --> 00:19:39.647
Not yet.

344
00:19:39.781 --> 00:19:40.948
You actually...

345
00:19:41.082 --> 00:19:42.482
you-you built a quantum
communication device.

346
00:19:42.617 --> 00:19:43.885
Can we-can we talk back?

347
00:19:44.018 --> 00:19:46.921
No. The hardware can't
replicate quantum signatures.

348
00:19:47.055 --> 00:19:48.923
I can. I've already
done it in my lab.

349
00:19:49.057 --> 00:19:50.558
I highly doubt it.
but...

350
00:19:54.194 --> 00:19:56.164
I suppose
we're gonna find out.

351
00:19:59.967 --> 00:20:01.401
Okay. I need to...

352
00:20:03.071 --> 00:20:04.772
Oh. Oh. wow.

353
00:20:15.650 --> 00:20:17.118
Ah.

354
00:21:13.875 --> 00:21:14.976
Good morning.

355
00:21:27.287 --> 00:21:29.157
Go to the ant.
consider her ways.

356
00:21:29.289 --> 00:21:30.525
and be wise.

357
00:21:30.825 --> 00:21:32.093
Do you know that?

358
00:21:34.162 --> 00:21:35.462
Hmm.

359
00:21:39.901 --> 00:21:41.636
We learn a lot from ants.

360
00:21:45.006 --> 00:21:46.439
For example. we. uh.

361
00:21:48.441 --> 00:21:51.612
we study them to. uh.
solve traffic problems.

362
00:21:54.849 --> 00:21:56.284
All sorts of things.

363
00:22:03.423 --> 00:22:05.793
I hear
your schooling's going well.

364
00:22:09.429 --> 00:22:10.731
I guess so.

365
00:22:15.303 --> 00:22:16.871
Good. Right.

366
00:22:54.308 --> 00:22:55.710
It's real.

367
00:23:03.416 --> 00:23:06.453
Shh. Do you hear that?

368
00:23:07.655 --> 00:23:09.090
Scared?

369
00:23:09.757 --> 00:23:11.058
No.

370
00:23:12.894 --> 00:23:14.028
Yeah.

371
00:23:17.832 --> 00:23:20.433
Mom says there's no
such thing as monsters.

372
00:23:25.239 --> 00:23:26.307
I'll go check it out.

373
00:23:26.439 --> 00:23:27.708
No!

374
00:23:29.409 --> 00:23:32.113
I can't lose you.

375
00:23:49.297 --> 00:23:51.399
So this is the transmitter.

376
00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:54.467
You can't turn it on for him.

377
00:23:55.703 --> 00:23:57.271
We don't know enough yet.

378
00:23:58.471 --> 00:23:59.674
I don't know.

379
00:23:59.807 --> 00:24:01.309
How else
are we going to find out?

380
00:24:02.710 --> 00:24:05.646
You're not worried
what they may be capable of?

381
00:24:08.916 --> 00:24:11.152
Are you inviting me
to speculate about aliens?

382
00:24:11.285 --> 00:24:13.821
Because people
often regret that.

383
00:24:13.955 --> 00:24:14.922
Yeah. I am.

384
00:24:15.056 --> 00:24:16.489
- Yeah?
- Mm-hmm.

385
00:24:17.058 --> 00:24:20.161
Okay. So. the coolest project
that I ever worked on.

386
00:24:20.294 --> 00:24:21.362
called the Argus 2.

387
00:24:21.494 --> 00:24:22.763
it's this bionic eye that.
like this machine

388
00:24:22.897 --> 00:24:24.598
that could send microelectrodes
from the optic nerve

389
00:24:24.732 --> 00:24:26.934
to the brain
and then. praise Jesus.

390
00:24:27.068 --> 00:24:28.336
the blind doth see.

391
00:24:28.468 --> 00:24:30.538
And just keeps getting better
and better and better.

392
00:24:30.671 --> 00:24:32.340
They get the software update
every year.

393
00:24:32.472 --> 00:24:34.275
and every two years.
a hardware update.

394
00:24:35.076 --> 00:24:36.177
Have you ever seen

395
00:24:36.310 --> 00:24:38.512
a three-year-old see
for the first time?

396
00:24:38.980 --> 00:24:39.814
No?

397
00:24:39.947 --> 00:24:42.650
It's-it's-it's everything.

398
00:24:43.250 --> 00:24:44.618
Anyways. next year.

399
00:24:44.752 --> 00:24:46.887
the Argus 5
is going to offer better vision

400
00:24:47.021 --> 00:24:49.657
than the perfectly healthy
biological eye.

401
00:24:50.358 --> 00:24:52.560
It's-it's crazy.
but why stop there?

402
00:24:52.693 --> 00:24:54.862
What about all the spectrums of
light that we can't even see?

403
00:24:54.996 --> 00:24:56.063
Ultraviolet spectrum.

404
00:24:56.197 --> 00:24:57.565
the X-ray vision even.

405
00:24:57.698 --> 00:24:59.166
or thermal. whatever.

406
00:25:00.134 --> 00:25:01.469
That's just the beginning.

407
00:25:01.969 --> 00:25:03.237
We start with the eyes.

408
00:25:03.371 --> 00:25:05.706
and then we're going to move on
and

409
00:25:05.840 --> 00:25:07.742
improve limbs beyond nature.

410
00:25:08.642 --> 00:25:11.212
improve livers beyond nature.
the heart beyond nature.

411
00:25:11.712 --> 00:25:15.649
and eventually pass the Rubicon
to the brain.

412
00:25:16.317 --> 00:25:18.652
We're going to take
all of our thoughts.

413
00:25:18.786 --> 00:25:20.621
all of our reasoning.
all of our intelligence.

414
00:25:20.755 --> 00:25:22.590
and we're going to put it
into a more durable container.

415
00:25:22.723 --> 00:25:24.492
Could be cloud-based
or silicon chip.

416
00:25:24.625 --> 00:25:25.793
something that's unbreakable.

417
00:25:25.926 --> 00:25:27.695
that can exist inside
of a black hole on the.

418
00:25:27.828 --> 00:25:31.265
on the tip of a pin
or in the spaces in between.

419
00:25:31.799 --> 00:25:33.034
And that...

420
00:25:33.300 --> 00:25:35.703
that is the end game
for homo sapiens.

421
00:25:36.404 --> 00:25:41.242
And I think that this is
just another version of us

422
00:25:41.675 --> 00:25:42.943
further down the road.

423
00:25:43.344 --> 00:25:44.812
Okay. but what about pain?

424
00:25:45.379 --> 00:25:46.881
Sorrow? Heartache?

425
00:25:47.648 --> 00:25:49.016
Profound loss?

426
00:25:49.917 --> 00:25:51.285
Regrets?

427
00:25:51.986 --> 00:25:53.020
What about 'em?

428
00:25:53.421 --> 00:25:55.122
Why-why would
eliminating that be bad?

429
00:25:55.423 --> 00:25:57.058
Because they shape
who we are as people.

430
00:25:57.191 --> 00:25:58.959
I think way more
than pleasures do.

431
00:25:59.093 --> 00:26:03.030
I mean. so much of who I am
and what I value came from.

432
00:26:03.931 --> 00:26:05.332
you know. painful experiences

433
00:26:05.466 --> 00:26:08.436
that happened in my life that
I had to grow and learn from.

434
00:26:08.569 --> 00:26:09.770
And change.

435
00:26:10.571 --> 00:26:11.540
I get that.

436
00:26:11.672 --> 00:26:14.041
but human suffering
as a whole. gone.

437
00:26:14.175 --> 00:26:15.576
- Can you see it?
- Yes. I see that.

438
00:26:15.709 --> 00:26:17.611
But I also see
a sterile intelligence

439
00:26:17.745 --> 00:26:19.480
on a path
with no interruptions.

440
00:26:19.847 --> 00:26:23.451
No purpose except to spread.
with no actual growth.

441
00:26:24.118 --> 00:26:25.920
And that. to me.
is not evolution.

442
00:26:26.053 --> 00:26:28.422
That is just an equation.

443
00:26:31.425 --> 00:26:34.795
And as awesome as your
bionic eye sounds. Charlie.

444
00:26:35.296 --> 00:26:38.065
I actually know a lot of those
patients have had them removed.

445
00:26:38.567 --> 00:26:39.400
Some.

446
00:26:39.534 --> 00:26:40.901
And some people are weird.

447
00:26:41.035 --> 00:26:44.939
And some people value other
things in scientific perfection.

448
00:26:45.072 --> 00:26:47.341
Some people accept
the parts of them

449
00:26:47.475 --> 00:26:50.444
that other people
might see as imperfect.

450
00:26:51.245 --> 00:26:52.446
Hmm.

451
00:26:53.582 --> 00:26:56.851
So. we are our flaws?

452
00:26:57.952 --> 00:26:59.453
And our mistakes.

453
00:27:03.824 --> 00:27:05.092
<i>Dr. Kask.</i>

454
00:27:05.893 --> 00:27:08.129
<i>you saw</i>
<i>how unbalanced Glassner was.</i>

455
00:27:08.262 --> 00:27:10.498
<i>You saw the threat he posed.</i>

456
00:27:10.764 --> 00:27:12.333
<i>Why did you choose to stay?</i>

457
00:27:13.501 --> 00:27:14.668
To help.

458
00:27:16.770 --> 00:27:18.772
<i>First contact was possible.</i>

459
00:27:20.908 --> 00:27:23.210
<i>Would you leave it</i>
<i>to an unbalanced nihilist</i>

460
00:27:23.344 --> 00:27:24.945
<i>to handle the introduction?</i>

461
00:27:26.180 --> 00:27:27.582
<i>This thought experiment</i>

462
00:27:27.715 --> 00:27:31.051
<i>dictates that the female rabbits</i>
<i>always give birth to pairs.</i>

463
00:27:31.185 --> 00:27:34.421
<i>And each pair consists</i>
<i>of one male and one female.</i>

464
00:27:34.556 --> 00:27:38.527
<i>Rabbits can't reproduce until</i>
<i>they are at least one month old.</i>

465
00:27:38.659 --> 00:27:40.895
She says she's very bright.

466
00:27:41.929 --> 00:27:43.565
<i>At the end of the second month.</i>

467
00:27:43.697 --> 00:27:45.567
<i>- the female...</i>
- Lucky for her.

468
00:27:47.168 --> 00:27:48.836
<i>When month three rolls around.</i>

469
00:27:48.969 --> 00:27:50.505
<i>the original pair of rabbits</i>

470
00:27:50.639 --> 00:27:53.007
<i>produces yet another</i>
<i>pair of newborns</i>

471
00:27:53.140 --> 00:27:55.510
<i>while their earlier</i>
<i>offspring grow to adulthood.</i>

472
00:27:55.644 --> 00:27:57.411
<i>This leaves three</i>
<i>pairs of rabbits.</i>

473
00:27:57.546 --> 00:27:59.514
<i>The order goes as follows:</i>

474
00:27:59.648 --> 00:28:04.985
<i>1. 1. 2. 3. 5. 8. 13. 21.</i>

475
00:28:37.586 --> 00:28:39.220
So. is Perry your husband?

476
00:28:39.588 --> 00:28:41.222
No. I'm a doctor.

477
00:28:41.355 --> 00:28:42.389
That's his daughter.

478
00:28:45.059 --> 00:28:46.393
How long have you been here?

479
00:28:46.661 --> 00:28:48.462
I haven't left the island
in three years.

480
00:28:48.597 --> 00:28:50.097
but it feels like 30.

481
00:28:53.033 --> 00:28:54.703
I don't know
how you stay sane.

482
00:28:54.835 --> 00:28:56.437
What makes you think I have?

483
00:29:02.577 --> 00:29:03.911
Is he always so...

484
00:29:12.453 --> 00:29:14.822
<i>Look. I'm not making</i>
<i>an excuse for him.</i>

485
00:29:16.056 --> 00:29:17.791
<i>because there's-there's none.</i>

486
00:29:20.060 --> 00:29:22.597
He lost his wife
and son four years ago.

487
00:29:22.731 --> 00:29:24.131
and it was bad.

488
00:29:28.135 --> 00:29:30.572
He never really accepted
what happened.

489
00:29:31.272 --> 00:29:32.674
What did happen?

490
00:29:33.207 --> 00:29:34.408
Well.

491
00:29:35.476 --> 00:29:37.111
there was a house fire.

492
00:29:37.646 --> 00:29:41.148
<i>He was in his lab</i>
<i>in an outbuilding 50 feet away.</i>

493
00:29:41.282 --> 00:29:43.752
<i>self medicated.</i>
<i>probably drunk.</i>

494
00:29:45.119 --> 00:29:48.122
Lucy? She was at a sleepover.

495
00:29:49.957 --> 00:29:51.626
But his wife and son...

496
00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:55.195
<i>Welcome</i>
<i>to Littlemouth's signal room.</i>

497
00:29:55.329 --> 00:29:57.599
<i>Perry wasn't even aware</i>
<i>there was a fire</i>

498
00:29:57.732 --> 00:29:59.300
<i>until the police woke him up.</i>

499
00:30:02.671 --> 00:30:04.506
<i>Is he dangerous?</i>

500
00:30:07.274 --> 00:30:09.544
He knows humans
matter in theory.

501
00:30:10.911 --> 00:30:12.781
but not in practice.

502
00:30:16.785 --> 00:30:18.385
<i>Just ask Lucy.</i>

503
00:30:47.682 --> 00:30:49.383
Thank you.

504
00:30:52.019 --> 00:30:55.923
Lucy. I want you
to watch this.

505
00:30:56.190 --> 00:30:58.760
This is a little piece
of forbidden magic

506
00:30:58.892 --> 00:31:02.429
that I learned
in the bazaars of Morocco

507
00:31:02.564 --> 00:31:07.868
from wise men who knew
how to turn steel into thin air.

508
00:31:08.536 --> 00:31:11.506
So. I want you
to count to three.

509
00:31:11.639 --> 00:31:13.708
then I want you
to blow on the napkin.

510
00:31:13.842 --> 00:31:17.311
Okay. One. two. three.

511
00:31:20.414 --> 00:31:21.516
Wait. wait. wait. Let me see.

512
00:31:21.649 --> 00:31:22.751
How'd you do that? Wait.

513
00:31:22.883 --> 00:31:24.084
Go to bed.

514
00:31:29.758 --> 00:31:32.059
- Here. let me help.
- You got school in the morning.

515
00:31:32.192 --> 00:31:33.762
- Go to bed.
- Thank you.

516
00:31:34.361 --> 00:31:35.730
Good night. sweetheart.

517
00:31:36.865 --> 00:31:37.931
Good night.

518
00:31:38.733 --> 00:31:39.967
Good night. Lucy.

519
00:31:44.539 --> 00:31:45.939
You didn't eat much.

520
00:31:48.409 --> 00:31:50.645
I-I've never had goat before.

521
00:31:51.780 --> 00:31:54.783
Okay. First impressions?

522
00:31:55.717 --> 00:31:57.317
Yeah. right.

523
00:31:57.451 --> 00:32:01.355
Uh. well. I think
it's completely legit.

524
00:32:01.488 --> 00:32:03.758
I mean. I've gone through
six months of his logs.

525
00:32:03.892 --> 00:32:04.992
and every single time

526
00:32:05.125 --> 00:32:06.427
I tried to find some
other explanation for it.

527
00:32:06.561 --> 00:32:07.928
he'd already disproved it.

528
00:32:08.061 --> 00:32:10.464
I mean. we're witnessing
actual alien chatter.

529
00:32:10.598 --> 00:32:11.965
We need to report this.

530
00:32:12.299 --> 00:32:13.835
What? To who?

531
00:32:13.967 --> 00:32:15.804
The IAA has guidelines
on post-detection.

532
00:32:15.936 --> 00:32:18.773
Do you want to have about
a dozen space agencies

533
00:32:18.907 --> 00:32:20.775
with all the bureaucrats
down here

534
00:32:20.909 --> 00:32:23.277
clusterfucking this thing
for the next decade?

535
00:32:23.410 --> 00:32:25.012
I mean. Sam.
I totally get it.

536
00:32:25.145 --> 00:32:26.013
and you're not wrong.

537
00:32:26.146 --> 00:32:27.782
However. Annika has a point.

538
00:32:27.916 --> 00:32:29.651
I mean. we're not
fucking around anymore.

539
00:32:29.784 --> 00:32:32.319
This is like a solid seven
on the RIO scale.

540
00:32:32.453 --> 00:32:34.188
Oh. for Christ sakes. Charlie.

541
00:32:34.321 --> 00:32:36.457
- You built quantum satellites.
- What?

542
00:32:36.591 --> 00:32:38.125
I thought you of all people

543
00:32:38.258 --> 00:32:39.794
would just want to run
with this thing.

544
00:32:39.928 --> 00:32:40.762
I-I do.

545
00:32:40.895 --> 00:32:42.196
Look. we discovered it.

546
00:32:42.897 --> 00:32:44.097
It's ours.

547
00:32:44.231 --> 00:32:45.365
Come on. that's fucked up.

548
00:32:45.499 --> 00:32:47.334
I mean. what if-if
I discovered Pluto

549
00:32:47.468 --> 00:32:49.169
I can just screw with it
any way I want to?

550
00:32:49.804 --> 00:32:51.673
Billionaires. they've taken
over space exploration

551
00:32:51.806 --> 00:32:54.107
because they have more
resources than entire nations.

552
00:32:54.241 --> 00:32:55.643
And I'm not exactly A-OK

553
00:32:55.777 --> 00:32:57.846
with some galactic
dick measuring contest

554
00:32:57.978 --> 00:32:59.781
where a few billionaires
get to determine

555
00:32:59.914 --> 00:33:01.448
the fate of all of humanity.

556
00:33:01.583 --> 00:33:04.819
Sam. listening is one thing.
but talking back?

557
00:33:05.820 --> 00:33:07.822
The risks of that
are mind-boggling.

558
00:33:08.857 --> 00:33:11.726
We don't know
if they're peaceful or hostile.

559
00:33:11.860 --> 00:33:12.861
And you're talking about

560
00:33:12.993 --> 00:33:15.563
sending a signal
the way they do.

561
00:33:15.697 --> 00:33:19.667
They'll know we're here
immediately from anywhere.

562
00:33:19.801 --> 00:33:22.236
You didn't say if you liked it.

563
00:33:25.005 --> 00:33:26.340
The goat.

564
00:33:29.042 --> 00:33:31.813
Yeah. uh.
it was fine.

565
00:33:32.479 --> 00:33:35.482
Now. we've spent six months
trying to decipher it

566
00:33:35.617 --> 00:33:38.085
and we still don't know
if they talk in calculus

567
00:33:38.218 --> 00:33:41.421
or interstellar Sanskrit
or in swirls of colour.

568
00:33:41.556 --> 00:33:42.757
Let me try.

569
00:33:42.891 --> 00:33:45.225
That kind of thing
might take centuries to crack.

570
00:33:45.894 --> 00:33:47.094
Give me a week.

571
00:33:51.131 --> 00:33:52.700
A week. that's all I ask.

572
00:33:53.166 --> 00:33:55.202
I hate goats.

573
00:33:58.673 --> 00:34:01.709
You know. they pair goats
with. uh. thoroughbreds.

574
00:34:01.843 --> 00:34:04.344
They call them
companion animals.

575
00:34:05.245 --> 00:34:07.381
You see. horses don't like
to be left on their own.

576
00:34:07.515 --> 00:34:09.082
They're herd animals.
and they. uh.

577
00:34:09.216 --> 00:34:10.384
well. they get very lonely.

578
00:34:10.518 --> 00:34:15.155
So the breeders will put a goat
in the horse pen

579
00:34:15.289 --> 00:34:18.225
to keep it settled
and manageable and docile.

580
00:34:18.358 --> 00:34:22.462
But the. uh.
the entire dynamic is...

581
00:34:23.263 --> 00:34:24.666
is very unnatural.

582
00:34:24.799 --> 00:34:27.434
First. you've taken a horse out
of its natural environment.

583
00:34:27.569 --> 00:34:29.604
and then you paper
over this perversion

584
00:34:29.737 --> 00:34:31.973
by forcing a companion on it.

585
00:34:32.105 --> 00:34:33.440
But some horses

586
00:34:35.275 --> 00:34:36.376
are different.

587
00:34:36.511 --> 00:34:37.612
They prefer solitude.

588
00:34:37.745 --> 00:34:42.215
and they see the goat
as an intruder.

589
00:34:43.417 --> 00:34:44.752
An invader.

590
00:34:45.553 --> 00:34:47.487
And so they'll do
what any animal would do

591
00:34:47.622 --> 00:34:49.057
when it feels threatened.

592
00:34:49.958 --> 00:34:50.992
I mean.

593
00:34:53.061 --> 00:34:55.228
horses don't even eat meat.

594
00:34:56.030 --> 00:34:59.934
But they will chew clean
through a goat's neck.

595
00:35:02.436 --> 00:35:03.605
Imagine that.

596
00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:07.274
And you know
what the owner does?

597
00:35:09.711 --> 00:35:10.845
Just buy us another goat.

598
00:35:10.979 --> 00:35:12.279
All right. I think
that's fucking enough.

599
00:35:12.412 --> 00:35:13.681
We're not waiting!

600
00:35:15.883 --> 00:35:18.251
Not a week! Not a day!

601
00:35:18.586 --> 00:35:20.320
You fix my hardware.

602
00:35:20.454 --> 00:35:22.523
You fix my software.

603
00:35:22.657 --> 00:35:25.158
My schedule. or I'm done!

604
00:35:30.632 --> 00:35:33.601
It's not the first time that
he's threatened to take his ball

605
00:35:33.735 --> 00:35:34.702
and go home.

606
00:35:34.836 --> 00:35:36.236
He's an unstable man.

607
00:35:36.370 --> 00:35:38.472
Yeah. well. it's all we can do
to keep him together with meds

608
00:35:38.606 --> 00:35:39.674
and duct tape.

609
00:35:42.076 --> 00:35:45.546
So I guess you realize the
other reason you're both here.

610
00:35:46.114 --> 00:35:48.683
The moment
that Perry is not functional.

611
00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:53.521
We get it.

612
00:35:53.821 --> 00:35:55.222
We're the replacements.

613
00:36:00.327 --> 00:36:04.364
So I will get you
your week. Annika.

614
00:36:05.332 --> 00:36:08.603
And I will smooth things
over with Perry tomorrow.

615
00:36:09.037 --> 00:36:10.237
All right?

616
00:36:30.323 --> 00:36:32.225
I'm worried that Perry's right.

617
00:36:33.460 --> 00:36:36.531
I think the only thing
that we can do is turn it on

618
00:36:37.065 --> 00:36:39.734
and let them know that we're
listening and hope they help.

619
00:36:39.867 --> 00:36:42.837
And that is
extremely dangerous.

620
00:36:45.305 --> 00:36:46.406
Maybe.

621
00:36:46.841 --> 00:36:48.341
But what would they want
from us?

622
00:36:48.475 --> 00:36:49.877
Resources.

623
00:36:50.011 --> 00:36:52.080
Nope. This universe
is crammed full of resources.

624
00:36:52.212 --> 00:36:54.882
And you and I both know
that our little tiny speck here

625
00:36:55.016 --> 00:36:56.951
of the Milky Way
is kind of a resource desert.

626
00:36:57.085 --> 00:36:58.186
Keep going.

627
00:36:58.318 --> 00:36:59.854
They could see us
as a threat.

628
00:36:59.987 --> 00:37:01.254
No. no.

629
00:37:01.388 --> 00:37:03.057
Look. you got the tech
that they got.

630
00:37:03.191 --> 00:37:05.793
You think they give a shit
about our stupid iPhones

631
00:37:05.927 --> 00:37:07.528
or our dumb smart bombs?

632
00:37:07.662 --> 00:37:08.696
Come on.

633
00:37:08.830 --> 00:37:09.964
Food.

634
00:37:10.098 --> 00:37:11.199
Us?

635
00:37:13.534 --> 00:37:15.803
I wouldn't touch me
with a 10 foot fork.

636
00:37:20.108 --> 00:37:23.410
Whichever way I-I try
to game this whole thing out.

637
00:37:25.113 --> 00:37:27.215
I can't find anything
to be afraid of.

638
00:37:28.116 --> 00:37:29.617
I can think of so many.

639
00:37:30.417 --> 00:37:32.086
Life is fragile.

640
00:37:33.121 --> 00:37:34.789
Fear keeps us safe.

641
00:37:35.089 --> 00:37:36.289
All right.

642
00:37:39.259 --> 00:37:42.797
Annika. our job
is to know the unknown.

643
00:37:42.930 --> 00:37:44.464
But now you don't want
to embrace it?

644
00:37:45.133 --> 00:37:46.901
You can't have it both ways.

645
00:37:49.704 --> 00:37:50.938
<i>Dr. Kask.</i>

646
00:37:51.072 --> 00:37:52.774
<i>why didn't you stop</i>
<i>Mr. Kaminsky</i>

647
00:37:52.907 --> 00:37:55.308
<i>from initializing</i>
<i>Littlemouth that evening?</i>

648
00:37:55.877 --> 00:37:57.410
<i>He never told me</i>

649
00:37:57.545 --> 00:37:59.781
because he knew
I'd try to stop him.

650
00:37:59.914 --> 00:38:01.448
<i>He didn't</i>
<i>consider the possibility</i>

651
00:38:01.582 --> 00:38:03.818
<i>that this alien</i>
<i>intelligence might be hostile?</i>

652
00:38:06.319 --> 00:38:09.524
<i>Charlie doesn't believe</i>
<i>intelligence can be hostile.</i>

653
00:38:12.059 --> 00:38:14.695
<i>For him.</i>
<i>intelligence doesn't waste.</i>

654
00:38:16.396 --> 00:38:17.965
It learns.

655
00:38:23.104 --> 00:38:24.038
<i>From mistakes.</i>

656
00:38:24.172 --> 00:38:26.841
<i>From mutations.</i>

657
00:38:26.974 --> 00:38:29.342
From curious
expressions in nature.

658
00:38:31.112 --> 00:38:32.547
<i>What do they want?</i>

659
00:38:34.414 --> 00:38:37.051
<i>What do we want</i>
<i>when we observe an ant colony</i>

660
00:38:37.185 --> 00:38:38.986
<i>halfway around the world?</i>

661
00:38:50.330 --> 00:38:52.033
<i>So. Charlie was always going</i>

662
00:38:52.166 --> 00:38:53.901
<i>to unlock Littlemouth.</i>

663
00:38:57.672 --> 00:38:59.006
Initialize.

664
00:38:59.140 --> 00:39:00.641
<i>Initializing.</i>

665
00:39:00.775 --> 00:39:02.375
<i>Because he believed</i>
<i>no harm would come of it.</i>

666
00:39:07.849 --> 00:39:10.383
<i>Initiation sequence successful.</i>

667
00:39:12.887 --> 00:39:16.090
<i>But you didn't</i>
<i>believe that. did you. Doctor?</i>

668
00:39:23.164 --> 00:39:24.999
<i>Uh. hey. Perry?</i>

669
00:39:26.200 --> 00:39:27.268
<i>Perry?</i>

670
00:39:27.969 --> 00:39:30.204
Well. uh. Perry.
you should. uh...

671
00:39:31.706 --> 00:39:33.507
<i>you should know</i>
<i>that I-I fixed it.</i>

672
00:39:34.342 --> 00:39:36.010
<i>We can talk back now.</i>

673
00:39:45.219 --> 00:39:48.455
<i>Welcome</i>
<i>to Littlemouth's signal room.</i>

674
00:40:03.738 --> 00:40:05.740
Get down here. Ten minutes.

675
00:40:07.275 --> 00:40:08.776
<i>Lowest level.</i>

676
00:40:13.446 --> 00:40:15.448
It's time to meet Littlemouth.

677
00:40:28.796 --> 00:40:31.165
<i>You have</i>
<i>reached the voicemail box of...</i>

678
00:40:31.299 --> 00:40:32.499
<i>Sam Houston.</i>

679
00:40:32.633 --> 00:40:34.769
<i>Please leave a message.</i>

680
00:40:36.871 --> 00:40:38.339
He said he'd wait.

681
00:40:42.410 --> 00:40:44.011
<i>Level C.</i>

682
00:40:47.315 --> 00:40:48.683
Take your time?

683
00:40:52.620 --> 00:40:54.454
Charlie tell me you didn't.

684
00:41:03.463 --> 00:41:08.468
At 1:24 AM
Littlemouth turns on.

685
00:41:08.836 --> 00:41:11.138
Perry. I object to this
on so many levels.

686
00:41:11.272 --> 00:41:13.708
But you won't do
anything about it. will you?

687
00:41:14.942 --> 00:41:18.478
So what you can do is check for
data variations when we go live.

688
00:41:18.612 --> 00:41:19.947
Uh. what are you...

689
00:41:20.081 --> 00:41:21.148
what are you going to say?

690
00:41:21.816 --> 00:41:22.883
Hello.

691
00:41:24.919 --> 00:41:26.020
How?

692
00:41:31.592 --> 00:41:33.194
Of all the data points.

693
00:41:33.327 --> 00:41:37.398
one sequence repeated itself
at a marginally greater rate.

694
00:41:37.598 --> 00:41:39.533
Littlemouth
will repeat that sequence

695
00:41:39.667 --> 00:41:43.037
and send it between here
and the antenna.

696
00:41:44.271 --> 00:41:45.873
But you don't even know
what that sequence means.

697
00:41:46.007 --> 00:41:47.341
Well. does an infant
have any idea

698
00:41:47.475 --> 00:41:50.344
what its first fumblings
at language mean? No.

699
00:41:50.478 --> 00:41:52.246
But they simply mimic
those more developed.

700
00:41:52.380 --> 00:41:53.748
- But the-
- Does the parent have any idea

701
00:41:53.881 --> 00:41:54.882
what the child means?

702
00:41:55.016 --> 00:41:56.717
No. but they know
what the child is saying.

703
00:41:57.818 --> 00:42:00.755
They're saying.
"I'm alive and I'm listening."

704
00:42:04.291 --> 00:42:08.262
Yet though we babble.
we do so mathematically.

705
00:42:08.396 --> 00:42:11.665
We will use
two universal constants.

706
00:42:11.799 --> 00:42:14.668
The speed of light
will be the unit of measurement.

707
00:42:15.202 --> 00:42:16.203
And primes.

708
00:42:16.337 --> 00:42:18.039
we will repeat
the code ten times.

709
00:42:18.172 --> 00:42:20.674
<i>The first interval will be two</i>
<i>times the speed of light.</i>

710
00:42:20.808 --> 00:42:22.209
<i>And the final interval.</i>
<i>therefore.</i>

711
00:42:22.343 --> 00:42:25.913
<i>will be the tenth prime 29</i>
<i>times the speed of light.</i>

712
00:42:27.548 --> 00:42:29.784
You're saying a lot
more than just hello.

713
00:42:29.917 --> 00:42:31.152
Yes.

714
00:42:31.285 --> 00:42:33.554
We're saying. "We've heard
you and we're logical."

715
00:42:34.755 --> 00:42:36.290
And. "We're here."

716
00:42:37.558 --> 00:42:38.893
Yes. that's the idea.

717
00:42:41.062 --> 00:42:43.397
By the way.
Sam won't stop it.

718
00:42:44.365 --> 00:42:45.433
There's no kill switch.

719
00:42:45.566 --> 00:42:47.268
And even if he could.
he never would.

720
00:42:47.401 --> 00:42:51.138
He's blinded by hubris in one
eye and glory in the other.

721
00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:55.443
Anything else
from the little goats?

722
00:43:02.349 --> 00:43:03.552
Yeah.

723
00:43:04.085 --> 00:43:05.119
Let's do it.

724
00:43:05.554 --> 00:43:06.387
What?

725
00:43:06.521 --> 00:43:07.988
I'm sorry. I-I gotta see this.

726
00:43:10.458 --> 00:43:11.792
Perry. you know.
you-you should. uh.

727
00:43:11.926 --> 00:43:12.993
you should say something.

728
00:43:13.127 --> 00:43:15.329
Like a quote
for posterity or something.

729
00:43:15.463 --> 00:43:17.164
What. like. "One small step"?

730
00:43:17.298 --> 00:43:19.934
or. "I am become Death.
destroyer of worlds"?

731
00:43:20.301 --> 00:43:21.570
I mean. something.

732
00:43:21.702 --> 00:43:23.237
Considering
what's about to happen. It's...

733
00:43:23.370 --> 00:43:24.839
Nothing is about to happen.

734
00:43:24.972 --> 00:43:26.140
That's the entire point.

735
00:43:27.041 --> 00:43:28.943
There's no war of the worlds.

736
00:43:30.878 --> 00:43:33.013
There's no grand enlightenment.

737
00:43:35.316 --> 00:43:36.851
Just a thundering silence.

738
00:43:39.653 --> 00:43:41.188
This is about insignificance.

739
00:43:41.322 --> 00:43:44.291
This is about
our smallness laid bare.

740
00:43:44.425 --> 00:43:49.964
There'll be no response
because we simply do not matter.

741
00:43:50.097 --> 00:43:52.800
Not our work. not our deeds.

742
00:43:52.933 --> 00:43:55.169
<i>Or our mistakes.</i>

743
00:43:56.637 --> 00:43:58.005
So there's your fucking quote.

744
00:43:59.574 --> 00:44:01.642
If it doesn't matter.
why build this?

745
00:44:04.411 --> 00:44:05.713
To prove it.

746
00:44:24.932 --> 00:44:26.233
Ta-da!

747
00:44:28.435 --> 00:44:29.303
There you go.

748
00:44:29.436 --> 00:44:32.574
Nothing. As predicted. Oof.

749
00:44:38.145 --> 00:44:40.147
So. when's it happening?

750
00:44:40.281 --> 00:44:41.315
<i>Five minutes ago.</i>

751
00:44:41.448 --> 00:44:42.816
Really? And?

752
00:44:42.950 --> 00:44:44.251
<i>And I'm done!</i>

753
00:44:44.385 --> 00:44:46.655
<i>Whoa. Annika.</i>
<i>uh. look. don't...</i>

754
00:44:54.495 --> 00:44:55.564
Whoa.

755
00:44:56.964 --> 00:44:58.265
Whah?

756
00:45:07.074 --> 00:45:08.610
Uh...

757
00:45:14.215 --> 00:45:16.217
<i>Backup power on.</i>

758
00:45:25.492 --> 00:45:27.061
<i>System offline.</i>

759
00:45:32.099 --> 00:45:34.703
Uh. Perry. Perry.
you should shut it off.

760
00:45:34.835 --> 00:45:36.270
Perry. shut-shut it off!

761
00:45:36.403 --> 00:45:37.438
- Shut it down!
- Shh!

762
00:46:01.929 --> 00:46:03.230
Annika. I got it.

763
00:46:03.598 --> 00:46:05.499
Why'd you turn it on. Charlie?

764
00:46:05.634 --> 00:46:06.568
Just hold on a sec.

765
00:46:09.604 --> 00:46:11.171
You need to come see this.

766
00:46:14.041 --> 00:46:16.176
<i>Officials have</i>
<i>yet to offer an explanation</i>

767
00:46:16.310 --> 00:46:17.545
<i>for the six seconds</i>

768
00:46:17.679 --> 00:46:19.980
<i>that interrupted almost</i>
<i>all global electronic</i>

769
00:46:20.114 --> 00:46:21.650
<i>and satellite communication.</i>

770
00:46:21.782 --> 00:46:25.019
<i>There are unconfirmed reports</i>
<i>of loss of life as hospitals.</i>

771
00:46:25.152 --> 00:46:28.255
<i>traffic signals</i>
<i>and aircraft have lost power.</i>

